005CD21FD5C24268871161C1C78C3C8F.description: Because of the economic growth of the 1950's and 1960's, numerous guest workers from southern Europe, Asia, and Africa immigrated to Western and Central Europe; however, after the economic downturn in the 1970's, these workers and their families often became targets of anti-immigration agitation and extreme nationalist political parties.

16FEB4DD427942B0BF862A3136B2D4F2.description: Intellectuals and youth reacted against perceived bourgeois materialism and decadence, most significantly with the revolts of 1968

241E89E0D4DD4749B290B9444E245E6E.description: Gay and lesbian movements worked for expanded civil rights, obtained in some nations, the right to form civil partnerships with full legal benefits or to marry.

BA7963F1649C41A39BE179F547686800.description: Green parties in Western and Central Europe challenged consumerism, urged sustainable development, and by the late 20th century, caustioned against globalization.

965A7A9C584A452EBEDDE7498D28B6D5.description: New voices gained prominence in political, intellectual and social discourse.

ACA83B12C4CE4B12BCA4B63BAF7F9A3B.description: Women attained high political office and increased their representation in legislative bodies in many nations.

5264A9BC1AB342A0AA04FCB0FA7B479F.description: New modes of marriage, partnership, motherhood, divorce, and reproduction gave women more options in their personal lives.

832F16B4C1D24AB5A979C928536E7EFA.description: With economic recovery after World War II, the birth rate increased dramatically (the baby boom), often promoted y government policy.

565227492437461C96009F17F245D49A.description: In Western Europe through the efforts of feminists, and in Eastern Europe and the Soviet Union through government policy, women finally gained the vote, greater educational opportunities, and access to professional careers, even while continuting to face social inequalities.

8A2E4A0101C747A6807C6B0F5B5AE4EB.description: During the world wars, women becaue increasingly involved in military and political mobilization as well as economic production.

93734F91FC15458FA4E020052D5990C6.description: The lives of women were defined by family and work responsilities economic change and feminism.

DA70219AAB5449B4BB4921D10BE3C092.description: New communication and transportation technologies multiplied the connections across space and time, transforming daily life and contributing to the proliferation of ideas and to globalization.

787D18E4304746E39D8FCA3C5E485642.description: Mass production, new food technologies, and industrial efficiency increased disposable income and create a consumer culture in which greater domestic comforts such as electricy, indoor plumbing, plastics, and synthetic fibers became available.

52A93D7B7E1944CA823918D27F1AC359.description: World War II decimated a generation of Russian and German men; virtually destroyed European Jewry; resulted in the murder of millions in other groups targeted by the Nazis including Roma, homosexuals, people with disabilities, and others; forced large-scale migrations; and undermined prewar class hierarchies

67F9D8E0A1D943E8908490F6EDB7AF61.description: World War I created a "lost generation" fostered disillusionment and cynicism, transformed the lives of women and democratized societies.

2EC1D966BD3845F586D99717CAA0580E.description: The 20th century was charcterized by large-scale suffering brough on by warfare and genocide as well as tremendous imporvements in the standard of living.

B18ECEAA60A54F59893FC0EAFF8BCF8F.description: Demographic changes, economic growth, total war, distruptions of traditional social patterns and competing definitions of freedom and justice altered the experiences of everyday life.

76E51BEAAE1647898DDE940B58408381.description: Increased imports of United States technology and popular culture after World War II generated both enthusiasm and criticism

F57EF058D71D4269BDBEAD729E0571CE.description: Throughout the century, a number of writers challenged traditional literary conventions, questioned Western valutes, and addressed controversial social and political issues.

AB552AC2549C4E39AA9DBD181055B90D.description: New movements in the visual arts, architechture, and music demolished existing asthetic standards, explored subconscious and subjective states and satirized Western society and its values.

66651301E1434C8D89F2A0E3B9E03DB1.description: During the 20th century, the arts were defined by experimentation, self-expression, subjectivity, and the increasing influence of the United Sates in both elite and popular culture

953231D0B94045B49A55E587AC270B37.description: Inreased immigration into Europe altered Europe's religious makeup, causing debate and conflict over the role of religion in social and political life

BDB5D52A11E241A389372D76F24CA511.description: Reform the Catholic Church found expression in the Second Vatican Council, which redefined the Churche's dogma and practices and started to redefine its relations with other religous communities.

AA119061BB4C49AA8F83683604D41295.description: The challenges of totalitarianism and communism in Central and Eastern Europe brough mixed responses from the Christian churches.

4CDB8B8CEA9D453AAF45FF1191FBE40A.description: Organized religion continued to play a role in European social and cultural life despite the challenges of military and ideological conflicts, modern secularism, and rapid social changes.

25357FEC1AAA4EAF8F82E9C8F0D8A8A2.description: Military techologies made possible industrialized warfare, genocide, nuclear proliferation, and the risk of global nuclear war.

EDC1EDAFE2CB4DDCBC8F6F4D11C2DE6A.description: Medical theories and technologies extended life but posed social and moral questions that eluded consensus and crosssed religious, political and philosophical perspectives.

306B1827C2764E9CB2DA34377405ECB9.description: The challenge to the certainties of the Newtonian universe in physics opened the door to uncertainty in other fields by undermining faith in objective knowledge, while also providing the knowledge necessary for the developments of nuclear weapons and power.

20FBF5299BCE42749843C51816908DA0.description: Science and technology yielded impressive material benefits but also caused immense destruction and posed challenges to objective knowledge.

375BBC37C68E40F1A2D7E33E293B67F2.description: The effects of world war and economic depression undermined this confidence in science and human reason, giving impetus to existentialism and producing postmodernism in the post-1945 period.

7AEE0ABABE304492858D14693C57B244.description: When World War I bean, Europeans were generally confident in the ability of science and technology to address human needs and problems despite the uncertainty created by the new scientific theories and psychology.

C0EFFC282D12454EBA30B33FC4ADC42B.description: The widely held belief in progress characteristic of much of the 19th century thought began to break down before World War I; the experience of the war intensified the sense of anxiety that permeated many facets of thought and culture, giving way by the century's end to a plurality of intellectual frameworks.

569816598946472D911CC65E57F8E71E.description: During the 20th century, diverse intellectual and cultural movements questioned the existence of objective knowledge and the ability of reason to arrive at the truth, and the role of religion in determining moral standards.

995A79E4C3BC4D65B4FC6512E4D99E22.description: The rise of new nationalism in Central and Eastern Europe brought peacefufl revolutions in most couuntries but resulted in war and genocide in the Balkans and instablity in some former Soviet republics.

51F5AD6E506C49A9804D056FFC47CB38.description: Following a long period of economic stagnation, Mikhail Gorbachev's internal reforms of perestroika and glasnost, designed to make the Soviet system more flexible, failed to stave off the collapse of the Soviet Union and the end of its hegemonic control over Eastern and Central Europe satellites.

DFF50FCDCF7340EDB754714565FFAE36.description: After 1956, Soviet leader Nikita Khrushchev's de-Stalinization policies failed to meet their economic goals within the Soviet Union and prompted revults in Eastern Europe.

F696AC997AF14FF4952DE72426EF1F84.description: Central and Eastern European nations within the Soviet bloc followed an economic model based on central planning extensive social welfare, and specialized production among bloc members.

79115DB5D2DE44ADB333F5DE5EC7A714.description: Eastern European nations were defined by their relationship with the Soviet Union, which oscillated between repression and limited reform, until Mikhail Gorbachev's policies led to the collapse of communist governments in Eastern Europe and the fall of the Soviet Union

27F974D228D74DC58ED15AEBF1C7575C.description: The expansion of cradle-to-grave social welfare programs in the aftermath of World War II, accompanied by high taxes, became a contentious domestic political issue as budgets of European nations came under pressure in the late 20th century.

EA1F4AC6413242AF9A007C9BCBCE000F.description: Marshall Plan funds from the United States financed an extensive reconstruction of industry and infrastructure and stimulated an extended period of growth in Western and Central Europe, often referred to as an "economic miracle" which increased the economic and cultural importance of consumerisim.

CFD5DF129572452FBCD7C0944F510A19.description: Postwar economic growth supported an increase in welfare benefits; however, subsequent economic stagnation led to criticism and limitations of the welfare state.

924BA6FCEA394D77A4F1C0CCAFE159B6.description: Despite attempts to rethink economic theories and policies and forge political alliances, Western democracies failed to overcome the Great Depression and were weakened by extremist movements.

BB7490D19DF849FFB747968D28F76E8C.description: Dependence on post-World War I American investment capital led to financial collapse when, following the 1929 stock market crash, the Unitd States cut off capital flows to Europe.

974E3A84E5B74D72A936FFD3C3DDE126.description: World War I debt, nationalistic tariff policies, overporduction, depreciated currencies, disrupted trade patterns, and speculation created weaknesses in economies worldwide.

327AB4C275604FC788741DCC6C12C279.description: The Great Depression, caused by weaknesses in international trade and monetary theories and practices, undermined Western European democracies and fomented radical political responses throughout Europe.

A3BABC40D5C94BEDACB6EF5159181680.description: After faiures to establish functioning democracies, authoritarian dictatorships took power in Central and Eastern Europe during the interwar period.

AFBA587C06034A18BF31B9BD675B52E2.description: Franco's falliance with Italian and German fascists in the Spanish Civil War - in which the Western democracies did not interven - represented a testing ground for World War II and resulted in authoriarian rule in Spain from 1936 to the mid-1970's

B88F878DBC8242F3BE0A2745DCC59E9A.description: Mussolini and Hitler rose to power by exploiting postwar bitterness and economic instability, using terror and manipulating the fledglind and unpopular domacracies in their countries.

B9341120A60245429EB12D2F568DAC04.description: Fascist dictatorships used modern technology and propaganda that rejected deoocratic institutions, promoted charismatic leaders, and glorified war and nationalism to lure the disillusioned.

DA30F4A21C5542F4917DB3687A844A3C.description: The ideology of fascism, with roots in the pre-World War I era, gained popularity in an environment of postwar bitterness, the rise of communism, uncertain transitions to democracy, and economic instablisty.

4F9969EAFCE54494A9CD5D6E606717D4.description: Stalin's economic moderniation of the Soviet Union came at a high price, including the liquidation of kulaks, famine in the Ukraine, purges of political rivals, unequal burdens placed on women, and the establishmentt of an oppressive political system.

5B64C243907F461A9E56FC7EBFFF2AAB.description: In order to improve economic performance, Lenin compromised with free-market principles under the New Economic Policy, but after his death, Stalin undertook a centralized program of rapid economic modernization.

DD8EA16E418B43139FFD26E2F4C612B6.description: The Bolshevik takeover prompted a protracted civil war between communist forces and their opponents, who were aided by foreign powers.

B5D4007D285C4FC980E007BA69EFD70C.description: Military and worker insurrections, aided by the revived Soviets, undermined the Provisional Government and set the stage for Lenin's long-planned Boslhevik Revolution and establishement of a communist state.

33BD9BFDF114496AB9510704B3BEC62F.description: In Russian, World War I exacerbated long-term problems of political stagnation, social inequality, incomplete industrialization, and food and land distribution, all while creating support for revolutionary change.

9431D50A9FD14CE589E4FCDC22B2326D.description: The Russian Revolution created a regime based on Marxist-Leninist theory

F4EC8DEF3FDC44E983B002103721FBD4.description: The stresses of economic collapse and total war engendered internal conflicts within  European states and created conflicting conceptions of the relationship between the individuals and the state, as demonstrated in the ideological battle between liberal democracy, communism, and fascism

2C8985A9D7F447F899632BE64B18EEE8.description: Despite indigenous nationalist movements, independence for many African and Asian territories was delayed until the mid- and even the late 20th century by the imperial powers reluctance to relinquish control, threats of interference from other nations, unstable economic and political systems, and Cold War strategic alignments.

ADC07DB868E24632B4BC2C0B3D2B6808.description: The Leauge of Nations distributed former German and Ottoman possessions to France and Great Britain through the mandate system, thereby altering the imperial balnce of power and creating a strategic interest in the Middle East for it's oil.

C785D92836724A7499A07621686A30C9.description: At the end of World War I, President Woodrow Wilson's principle of national self-determination raised expectation in the non-European world for freedom from colonial domination - expectations that led to international instablity.

A9188D80A2744209BEB6683E6D2EBF70.description: The process of decolonization occured over the course of the century with varying degrees of cooperation, interference, or resistance from European imperialist states.

FA4620AC80594A86BD3D4AC7A2C5DD68.description: Nationalist and separatist movements, along with ethnic conflicts and ethnic cleansing, periodically distruped the post-World War II peace.

98DF2ADC37214DFF81740B6783A17937.description: On of the major continuing challenges to countries in the EU is balancing national sovereignty with the responsiblities of membership in an economic and political union.

F0D07F535B544271AF386BB7B4D377B5.description: As the economic allieance known as the European Coal and Steel Community envisioned as a means to spur postwar economic recovery, developed into the European Economic Community (EEC or Common Market) and the European Union (EU), Eurpe experienced increasing economic and political integration and efforts to establish a shared European identy.

2DCB1B2EAD7C4ECD806CE0D8F6BDE32B.description: In response to the destructive impact of two world wars, European nations began to set aside nationalism in favor of economic and political integration, forming a series of transnational unions that grew in size and scope over the second half of the 20th century.

99FB20AB022C499AAEDD34D2F7CF6A69.description: The collapse of the USSR in 1991 ended the Cold War and led to the establishment of capitalist economies throughout Eastern Europe, Germany was reunited, the Czechs and the Slovaks parted, Yugoslavia dissolved, and the European Union was enlarged through admission of former Eastern bloc countries.

AFBA62C3CD4443B39FCAFE974DE20BF7.description: Countries east of the Iron Curtain came under the military, political and economic domination of the Soviet Union within the Council for Mutual Econpomic Assistance (COMECON) and the Warsaw Pact.

E95886AEB2DA4603B4660320BD29CE8A.description: The United States excerted a strong military, political, and economic influence in Western Europe, leading to the creation of world monetary and trade systems and geopolitical alliances such as the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)

A9FF98EF657D4379BEF3D178D1BD7D31.description: The Cold War played out on a global stage and invovled propaganda campaigns; covert actions;limited "hot wars" in Asia, Africa, Latin America, and the Carbbean; and the arms race with the threat of a nuclear war.

1F5E15662D8C4A68A4D40F08AC1CD7D0.description: Despite efforts to maintain international cooperation through the newly created United Nations, deep-seated tensions between the USSR and the West led to the division of Europe, which was referred to in the West as the Iron Curtain.

FC2CA1653BC24B39B53CB8FA285E708B.description: As World War II ended, a Cold War between the liberal democratic West and the communist East began, lasting nearly half a century.

B280EBD784D541AD9D2B32AB73B943BB.description: Fueled by racism and anti-Semitism, Nazi Germany - with the cooperation of some of the other Axis powers and collaborationist governments - south to establish a "new racial order" in Europe which culminated with the Holocaust.

C8823CC1B7CD4D4797282F7E634211D3.description: American and British industrial, scientific, and technological power and the all-out military commitment of the USSR contributed critically to the Allied victories.

87DF0B8734BE4B8C822E3E663C24F095.description: Germany's Blitzkrieg warfare in Europe combined with Japans attacks in Asia ant the Pacific, brought the Axis powers early victories.

896FB140556B4E55917FC87C950CF04A.description: French and British fears of another war, American isolationism, and deep distrust between Western democratic, capitalist nations, and the communist Soviet Union allowed fascist states to rearm and expand their territory.

F4456D6EA0384EB89AD531D52CC56CE9.description: In the interwar period, fascism, extreme nationalism, racist ideologies, and the failure of appeasement resulted in catastrophe of World War II, presenting a grave challenge to European civilization.

C6B4DE98550542E8AF8428B7B51DC533.description: The Versailles settlement, particularly its provisions on the assignment of guilt and reparations for the war, hindered the German Weimar Republic's ability to establish a stable and legitimate political and economic system.

5E978754407F4A1E94452792D104C97A.description: The League of Nations, created to prevent future wars, was weakened from the outset by non participation of major powers, including the United States, Germany and the Soviet Union.

E49A2A323FD4442C882DFBD4E65C8E87.description: Wilsonian idealism clashed with postwar realities in both the victorious and defeated states. Democratic successor states emerged from former empires and eventually succumbed to significant politcal, economic, and diplomatic crises.

D47B051ABBB64BD69A379F414CA88CE1.description: The conflicting goals of the peace negotiators in Paris pitted diplomatic idealism against the desire to punish Germany, producing a settlment that satisfied few.

260767C60B2548BFBAADBB0E5CA34655.description: The relationship of Europe to the world shifted significantly with the globalization of the conflict, the emergence of the United States as a world power, and the otherthrwow of European empires.

108A13E3BA1C42229F25A402A757C9CB.description: the war in Europe quickly spread to non-European theaters, transforming the war into a global conflict.

7BD9B136C7FA4E08B58A9200011C6A53.description: The effects of military stalemate and total war led to protests and isurrection in the belligerent nations and eventually to revolutions that changed the international balance of power.

2D380862D9FA4BD485F605606D746C75.description: New technologies confounded traditional military strategies and led to massive troop losses.

327EF35A9FC944B1A44EFFE6E345D40F.description: A variety of factors - including nationalism, military plans the alliance system, and imperial competition - turned a regional dispute in the Balkans into World War I.

18AACD8B40004B30839BF14132D627DE.description: World War I, caused by a complex interaction of long- and short-term factors, resulted in immense losses and disruptions for both victors and vanquished.

A0C21E0C971F45F8822D49658AA9B61D.description: Total war and political instability in the first half of the 20th century gave way to a polarized state order during the Cold War and eventually to efforts at transnational union

0A9E4D7A6CB1451287864C054EA38FB4.description: Modern art, including Impressionism, Post-Impressionism, and Cubism, moved beyond the representational to the subjective, abstract and expressive and often provoked audiences that believed that art should reflect shared and idealized values such as beauty and patriotism.

0EC9FC7BDD394023996754D2BA5CF36C.description: Developments in natural sciences such as quantum mechanics and Einstein's theory of relativity undermined the primacy of Newtonian physics as an ojbective description of nature.

537B578BFAC5434189833914CD06A625.description: Freudian psychology provided a new account of human nature that emphasized the role of the irrational and the struggle between the consicious and subconscious.

A140C2B31E054CDA99BFC3EB1865A9D6.description: Philosophy largely moved from rational interpretations of nature and human society to an emphasis on irrationality and impulse, a view that contriuted to the belief that conflict and struggle led to progress.

2E18281436C347EB8705E2B421D8DB2D.description: A new relativism in values and the loss of confidence in the objectivity of knowledge led to modernism in intellectual and cultural life.

5AC32B10E093401EBA498EA9460BA714.description: Realists and materialists themes and attitudes influenced art and literature as painters and writers depicted the lives of ordianry people and drew attention to the social problems.

4D84871FCCAE4D528483C7DC74AD3DD1.description: Marx's scientific socialism provided a systematic critique of capitalism and a derministic analysis of society and historical evolution.

8B41C588BD0C4847B9B46CD88EF1B000.description: Charles Darwin provided a rational and material account of biological change and the development of human beings as a species, and inadvertently a justification for racialist theories known as Social Darwinsim.

50C3119A5E394C22AE824D0A8588A3F1.description: Positivism, or the philosophy that science alone provides knowledge emphasized the rational and scientific analysis of nature and human affairs.

7EAB41B041E34B0AAE1234CE852C3106.description: Following the revolutions of 1848, Europe turned toward realist and materialist worldview.

474F1914D1FF4F27864CED23C5BE1875.description: Romantic writers expressed similar themes while responding to the Industrial Revolution and to various political revolutions.

7C7B086E0636456BAA4089AAABF897B1.description: Romantic artists and composers broke from classical artistic forms to emphasize emothion, nature, individuallyty, intution, the supernatural and national histories in their works.

B464F6699C91407FB340015DBA67F8B0.description: Romanticism broke with neoclassical forms of artistic representation and with rationalism, placing more emphasis on intution and emotion

97A72906AB0E4A75AD8F2B038EBE3B0D.description: European ideas and culture expressed a tension between objectivity and scientific realism on one hand and subjectivity and individual expression on the other.

95213BB2665743B9A08D123FD7280025.description: As non-Europeans became educated in Western values, they challenged European imperialism through nationalist movements and/or by modernizing their own economies and societies.

FC4C04F3E95A46E7B4D13A3629F50DA5.description: Imperial encounters with non-European peoples influenced the styles and subject matter of astists and writers and provoked debate over the acquisition of colonies.

237A0584B49F4C43A9BFA61DDAE16A9B.description: Imperialism created diplomatic tensions among European states that strained alliance systems.

5342627133B543AF9E120B35A93EF485.description: Imperial endeavors significantly affected society, diplomacy and culture in Europe and created resistance to foreign control abroad.

C23CB0B9B3F848638CFE8FD173ADC42D.description: Advances in medicine supported European control of Africa and Asia by preserving European lives.

E3912DC17790417A8B2C221C365EAD07.description: Communications and transportation technolgies allowed for the creation of European empires.

466EF79B3411454D9F72AC577C51BCF3.description: The development of advanced weaponry invariably ensured the military superiority of Europeans over colonizated areas.

F5C1BF454FD04C34B9C566C7BF4596F2.description: Industrial and technological developments (i.e., the second industrial revolution) facilitated European control of global empires.

192C69B66F31481EA875B960E68454E8.description: Europeans justified imperialism through an ideology of cultural and racial superiority

9CCAAE7DBD83471D8AB51067903F8906.description: The search for raw materials and markets for manufactured goods, as well as strategic and nationalistic considerations, drove Europeans to colonize Africa and Asia, even as European colonies in the Americas brook free politically, if not economically.

6C4E89E7C43F4A42B18D80FC31D2AC22.description: European national rivalries and strategic concerns fostered imperial expansion and competition for colonies.

A946F7B1936949838F688D0720EB1A1D.description: European nations were driven by economic, political, and cultural motivations in their new imperial ventures in Asia and Africa.

E760675E9A8C40E5ADBF9F9636E1A419.description: A variety of motives and methods led to the intensification of European global control and increased tensions among the Great Powers

247A91E56D4A455E85C1AB4503B81C29.listId: E Nationalist tensions in the Balkans drew the Great Powers into a series of crises, leading up to w
247A91E56D4A455E85C1AB4503B81C29.description: Nationalist tensions in the Balkans drew the Great Powers into a series of crises, leading up to World War I.

DA1E7D01485C4F72B2E4F191E3EE847B.description: Bismarck's dismissal in 1890 eventually led to a system of mutually antagonistic alliances and heightened international tensions.

6B26744F3B6D4966A0484DB48AD9B168.description: After 1871, Bismarck attempted to maintain the balance of power through a complex system of alliances directed at isolating France.

7EEE10E9928A4271AF24CBC87A423BE3.description: Bismarck employed diplomacy and industrialized warfare and weaponry and the manipulation of democratic mechanisms to unify Germany .

487C30888DBD42E1A01389F7EB8C0397.description: Cavour's Realpolitik strategies, combined with the popular Garibaldi's military campaigns led to the unification of Italy.

3B1E2C909BBE4587AB806FA8B4444AFB.description: The unification of Italy and Germany transformed the European balance of power and led to efforts to construct a new diplomatic order.

FFE8140B21D84159ABF943D88C3FAC37.description: In Russia, Autocratic leaders pushed through a program of reform and modernization, which gave rise to revolutionary movements and eventuall the Revolution of 1905.

2EDBF9181418437791E141BC106F6817.description: The creation of the dual monarchy of Austria-Hungry, which recognized the poliltical power of the largest ethnic minority, was an attempt to stablize the state by reconfiguring national unity.

722EB3F2529D4148B2E75D65096BD584.description: A new breed of conservative leaders, including Napoleon III, Cavour, and Bismarck, co-opted the agend of nationalists for the purposes of creating or strengthening the state.

7EA041A099B14ABCBE67B4D63E655CE6.description: The Crimean War demonstrated the weakness of the Ottoman Empire and contributed to the breakdown of the Concert of Europe, thereby creating the conditions in which Italy and Germany could be unified after centuries of fragmentation.

B224CF4ADEF8441DB29DCF41462A19BA.description: The breakdown of the Concert of Europe opened the door for movements of national unifaction in Italy and Germany as well as liberal reforms elsewhere.

730C94DCD88547BCA2A8F3B901211A6A.description: The revolutions of 1848 challenged the conservative order and led to the breakdown of the Concert of Europe

A6C1AAB1FD3D481C896A1FD343D2C24E.description: In the first half of the 19th century, revolutinaries attempted to destroy the status quo.

68CE8CECCCCF4BDE8353AC86B317D1F0.description: Conservatives re-established control in many European states and attempted to suppress movements for change and, in some areas, to strengthen adherence to religious authorieties.

43694EF0D9BA4DBC8A409BC922CF57C5.description: Metternich, architect of the Concert of Europe, used it to suppress nationalist and liberal revolutions.

822A9CED2C954F269F50C11F50DEA7C3.description: The Concert of Europe (or Congress System)  sought to maintain the status quo through collective action and adherence to conservatism.

9F9E9EFDA00646A9BC284EEFC96EE8EE.description: European states struggled to maintain internatinal stablity in an age of nationalism and revolutions.

BB4ACCDA902D4BBD9F63F799CD9FA33A.description: Various private nongovernmental reform movements sought to lift up the deserving poor and end serfdom and slavery.

DF848D49CC85402D948D2891AF60443C.description: Feminists pressed for legal, economic, and political rights for women as well as improved working conditions.

A01A6203D59845438AD8D1B126C2A1DF.description: Workers established labor unions and movements promoting social and economic reforms that also developed into political parties.

2B023CB541604DD485762655B4ED15BF.description: Mass-based political parties emerged as sophisticated vehicles for social, economic and plitical reform.

F73B1B740C374DE7A7B83E93170E2F94.description: Political movements and social organizations responded to the problems of industrialization.

EC9E3FBC7C5B441EB3D5896B18306A43.description: Governments promoted cumpolsory public education to advance the goals of public order, nationalism and economic growth.

5CEB21C0A07B40939CBF78D7E9017BED.description: Government reforms transformed unhealthy and overcroweded cities by modernizing infrastructure, regulating public helath, reforming prisons, and establishing modern police forces.

C2E65F79E90D458CAB11D02BFCCAA0C4.description: Liberalism shifted from laissez-faire to interventionist economic and social policies on behalf of the less privileged; the policies were based on a rational approach to reform that addressed the impact of the Industrial Revolution on the individual.

20ECAB76DB0D4095B7426C956DC07B0F.description: Governments responded to the problems created or exacerbated by industrialization by expanding their functions and creating modern bureaucatic states.

27541C7BA962415E9F721BF3D5B5DE22.description: A form of Jewish nationalism, Zionism developed in the late 19th century as a response to growing anti-Semitism in both western and eastern Europe.

EA28924508A3457E9E4FE1B2B670AE98.description: Nationalists encouraged loyalty to the nation in a variety of ways, including romantic idealism, liberal reform, political unification, racialism with a concomitant anti-Semitism, and chauvinism justifying national aggrandizement.

39974ACC748A44F8963591E4256757CF.description: Anarchists asserted that all forms of governmental authority were unnecessary and should be overthrown and replaced with a society based on voluntary cooperation.

C223117CD9754CA4B6F0E5F81B40ACC1.description: Socialists called for a fair distribution of society's resources and wealth and evolved from a utopian to a Marxist scientific critique of capitalilsm.

A4BD34CA940E4235BB0643993EF2FAF1.description: Conservatives developed a new ideology in support of traditional political and religious authrities, which was based on the idea that human nature was not perfectible.

A7C2FD1285F544CBB1AB81A57D89F215.description: Radicals in Britain and republicans on the continent demanded universal male suffrange and full citizenship without regard to wealth and property ownership; some argued that such rights should be extended to women.

49CBC552C92D48D897E226EF09B646BE.description: Liberals emphasized popular sovereignty, individual rights, and enlightened self-interest but debated the extent to which all groups in society should actively participate in its governance.

D3EDABB4F4FF40B29F785CCEE3495818.description: Ideologies developed and took root throughout society as a response to industrial and political revolutions.

2C6346C01AB34A89A7F854BCB1933BB7.description: The problems of industrialzation provoked a range of ideological, governmental, and collective responses.

FE1BA39C347146DCBBF1BE57C11E615C.description: Because of the persistence of primitive agricultural practices and land-owning patterns, some areas of Europe lagged in industrialization while facing famine, debt, and land shortages.

BA89618AFA2C4193BF30B3C822FBA001.description: New efficient methods of transportation and other innovations created new industries, improved the distribution of goods, increased consumerism, and enhanced the quality of life.

327FAE1FDD9E4D13BEB88AE3A14BBE2E.description: Industrialization and mass marketing increased both the production and demand for a new range of consumer goods - including clothing, processed foods, and labor-saving devices - and created more leisure opportunities.

E042FE86815443E8994D77C9CE599895.description: A heightened consumerism developed as a result of the second industrial revolution.

F660277E7B7D46588DEFBF7D2C2CE251.description: Leisure time centered increasingly on the family or small groups, concurrent with the development of activities and spaces to use that time.

1ED105A8B47C4704A2B313322CF60318.description: Economic motivations for marriage, while still important for all classes, diminished as the middle-class notion of companionate marriage began to be adopted by he working classes.

2C4798ED7A8A48A3AE790BD7DC24E781.description: By the end of the century, wages and the quality of life for the working class improved because of laws restricting the labor of children and women, social welfare programs, improved diet, and the use of birth control.

3A60B1DF33754E0C8287510BA19E469C.description: Brougeois families became focused on the nuclear family and the cult of domesticity, with distinct gender roles for men and women.

86C8D50C6DC34CDA8085B4C37EAEAEDE.description: Over time, the Industrial Revolution altered the family structure and relations for bourgeois and working-class families.

F0D85903DF4940E9932D47B547847435.description: With migration from rural to urban areas in industrialized regions, cities experienced overcrowding, while affected rural areas suffered declines in available labor as well as weakened communities.

861974553F3D4672A046610319BF7CA7.description: Along with better harvests caused in part by the commercialization of agriculture, industrialization promoted population growth, longer life expectancy, and lowered infant mortality.

B7A9368C29B44B55B0934C81809CF4F8.description: Europe experienced rapid population growth and urbanization, leading to social dislocations.

BE0924790AB24B2C9AD023D34A382772.description: Class identity developed and was reinforced through participation in philathropic, political and social associations among the middle classes, and in mutual aid societies and trade unions among the working classes.

00288284A35A4874A7E99B9C68A13D54.description: In some less industrialized ares of Europe, the dominance of agricultural elites persisted into the 20th century.

B962B23EB6F0447B83418DB474EC171A.description: In industrialized areas of Europe (ie, western and northern Europe), socioeconomic changes created divisions of labor that led to the development of self-conscious classes, such as the proletariat and the bourgeoisie.

766423682AC44819B8C7CC0197AD7C3C.description: Industrialzation promoted the development of new classes in the industrial regions of Europe.

6091CBE6D1D8427F9BF2061FF71399BB.description: The experiences of everyday life were shaped by industrialzation, depending on the level of industrial development in a particular location.

5BE850EC42B544FAB2D0E378ACFAC4A5.description: Volatile business cycles in the last quarter of the 19th century led corporations and governments to try to manage the market through monopolies, banking practices, and tariffs.

16EF7E3E65F44E4ABA0D5EC7FFC9DAD7.description: New technologies and means of communication and transportation - including railroads - resulted in more fully integrated national economies, a higher level of urbanization, and a truly global economic network.

2758417ED4AD4EE1A62FC1C42E96A2C1.description: Mechanization and the factory system became the predominant modes of production by 1914.

195264507A5640FEAC9B0FF6F55C6F60.description: During the second industrial revolution (c 1870-1914), more areas of Europe experienced industrial activity, and industrial processes increased in scale and complexity.

22F64F76301E4CD79D204B7BCC67B8B6.description: A combination of factors including geography, lack of resources, the dominance of traditional landed elites, the persistence of serfdom in some areas, and inadequate government soponsorhsip accounted for eastern and southern Europe's lag in industrial development.

7BC86291BC5244DAAE7F6E19C03289E1.description: Industrialization in Prussia allowed the state to become the leader of a unified Germany, which subsequently, underwent rapid industrialization under government sponsorship.

CAED49484FF640F9B7E2EB43FC7F0FDD.description: France moved toward industrialization at a more gradual pace than Great Britain, with government support and with less dislocation of traditional methods of production.

FA0D0C5B93B543C898552420F47C838B.description: Following the British example, industrialization took root in continental Europe, sometimes with state sponsorship.

28437E946F9C4AB18295759282A7F642.description: Britain's parliamentary government promoted commercial and industrial interests because those interest were represented in Parliament.

2FBF4DFB68F74B07BF6620F354DBE7C9.description: Economic institutions and human capital such as engineers, inventors, and capitalists helped Britain lead the process of industrialization,  largely through private initiative.

6E4C5E452E7F4EEE88CBB7EC2BF3AF8B.description: Britain's ready supplies of coal, iron ore, and other essential raw materials promoted industrial growth.

CC42F73CBB7C4DE19F94F49DBE3394B1.description: Great Britain established its industrial dominance through the mechanization of textile production, iron and steel production, and new transportation systems.

B27637A4D0374078999FA72540476C34.description: The Industrial Revolution spread from Great Britain to the continent, where the state played a greater role in promoting industry.

6C96897396234555916540908C5E75BE.description: The concentration of the poor in cities led to a greater awareness of poverty, crime, and prostitution as social problems, and prompted increased efforts to police marginal groups.

1DF455E6D9C24C56A7A2C65430CED22E.description: The growth of cities eroded traditional communal values, and city governments trained to provide protection and a healthy environment.

C26881D145D249D295FC4E3A5CB18FE5.description: The Agricultural Revolution produced more food using fewer workers; as a result, people migrated from rural areas to the cities in search of work.

C002D894B7DF4C73BE9B8E1867160115.description: Cities offered economic opportunities, which atracted increasing migration from rural areas, transforrming urban life and creating challenges for the new urbanites and their families.

9833F75C45084CE7881471908EE650CB.description: As infant and child mortality decreased and commercial wealth increased, families dedicated more space and resources to children and child-rearing, as well as privae life and comfort.

0EDCA75CE861424FB158D022A6A67EA2.description: Although the rate of illegitimate births increased in the 18th century, population growth was limited by the European marriage pattern and, in some areas, by the early practice of birth control.

B8BFA48B83C944EFA715F2791E2E9A95.description: By the 18th Century, family and private life reflected new demographich patterns and the effects of the commercial revolution.

6D6EFD34E9B049F6B344516497F02FE5.description: The consumer revolution of the 18th century was shaped by a new concern for privacy, encouraged the purchase of new goods for homes, and created new venues for leisure atvities

B2BCD5FBE3104FA88B3243D9988F3C6A.description: In the 18th century, plague disappeared as a major epidemic disease, and inoculation reduced smallpox mortality.

4C7E44A8037544D49703416527B9221D.description: By the middle of the 18th century, higher agricultural productivity and improved transportation increased the food supply, allowing populations to grow and reducing the number of demographic crises (a process known as the Agricultural Revolution.

B645059EC50A41B7B0691CAC559B65AF.description: In the 17th century, small landholdings, low-productivity agricultural practices, poor transportation, and adverse weather limited and disrupted the food supply, causing periodic famines. By the 18th century, Europeans began to escape from the Malthusian imbalance between population and the food supply, resulting in steady population growth.

D85CC804D2374C86877FC097A5C8557C.description: The experiences of everyday life were shaped by demographic, environmental, medical and technological change.

3B2768AB225946B5B944FFB91B6D8F6B.description: Romanticism emerged as a challenge to Enlightenment rationality.

88E725D282DB4FA59712C69E9CB45CF6.description: Revolution, war and rebellion demonstrated the emotional power of mass politics and nationalism

590C631F5C60468BA15D9E0C1F942B28.description: Roussseau questioned the exclusive reliance on reason and emotions in moral improvement of self and society.

1B9FABC587A646F1BB0AFF9EC384C8DF.description: While Enlightenment values dominated the world of European ideas, they were challenged by the revival of public sentiment and feeling.

8C7CD5C7C3384E8A82C47AF41727B7E8.description: Artistic movements and literature also reflected the outlook and values of commercial and bourgeois society as well as new Enlightenment ideals of political power and citizenship.

580956AECD0846D88E586726DDAB535F.description: Unitl about 1750, Baroque art and music promoted religious feeling and was employed by monarchs to glorify state power.

FC44BD13126149609A462A18B42BF5F7.description: The arts moved from the celebration of religious themes and royal power to an emphasis on private life and the public good.

A8E007BEF2E341B29A9CAC8DFD31B564.description: By 1800, most governments had extended toleration to Christian minorities and, in some states, civil equality to Jews.

7F28DDF5D5234FF090729CDBC882105A.description: Religion was viewed increasingly as a matter of private rather than public concern

54BFBAC03E9B4E4EB5D5892A27A45443.description: Intellectuals, including Voltaire and Dierot, developed new philosophies of deism, skepticism, and atheism.

6331647B62254714937001166F0B6C30.description: During the Enlightenment, rational analysis of religious practices led to natural religion and the demand for religious toleration.

9CB2E2143F494565A6B3AFD810AFE3CB.description: Mercantilist theory and practice were challenged by new economic ideas, such as Adam Smith's, espousing free trade and free market.

148AE839E42B44B9916875F8A6A4EA27.description: Political theories, such as John Locke's conceived a a society as composed of individuals driven by self-interest and argued that the state originated  in the consent of the governed (i.e. social contract) rather than in divine right or tradition.

22690DB56F334F6CB3E469DFE7636A79.description: New political and economic theories challenged absolultism and mercantilim

6F5A8C65EA564A74892EC13F6357B7F9.description: Natural sciences, literature, and popular culture increasingly exposed Europeans to representations of peoples outside Europe

DBC867DDF0C54A1A8CC95C446936859D.description: Despite censorship, increasingly numerous and varied printed materials served a growing literate public and led to the development of public opinion

72D66D357A1544BB871F15670731EC58.description: A variety of institutions, such as salons, explored and disseminated Enlightenment culture

48A493110C8842B8A61F1257ED1E253C.description: New public venues and print media popularized the Enlightenment ideas

30500C3BF7B94E8EA29495BCF666651E.description: Despite the principles of equality espoused by the Enlightenment and the French Revolution, intellectuals such as Rousseau offered new arguments for the exclusion of women from political life, which did not go unchallenged.

B9FA0BBDBB5E4BBEAC5556F3018D8F01.description: Locke and Rousseau developed new political models based on the concept of natural rights.

B525AEA75E924A0FA84B480A59CD4744.description: Intellectuals such as Voltaire and Diderot began to apply the principles of the Scientific Revolution to society and human institutions.

3797B0A676594025BC19BAAE044D502A.description: Rational and empirical thought challenged traditional values and ideas.

D995F6B3E4454CAD96ECC1C5F0035EC7.description: The popularization and dissemination of the Scientific Revolution and the application of its methods to political, social and ethical issues led to an inccreased, although not unchallenged, emphasis on reason in European culture.

AB526DADDF6642A68A7488FD4BE49B60.description: Portuguese, Dutch, French, and British rivalries in Asia culminated in British domination in India and Dutch control of the East Indies.

8983611D4298464F98A3DA4A6194E16C.description: European sea powers vied for Atlantic influence throughout the 18th century.

64CFF6B0E34F48A0A5E3ADC620CAF447.description: Commerical rivalries influenced diplomacy and warfare among European states in the early modern period.

94BF41BDBB2148B7B3F5EE6665A3886D.description: Foreign lands provided raw materials, finished goods, laborers, and markets for the commercial and industrial enterprises in Europe.

77F4744456454CA89BA3DC8D7C769623.description: The importation and transplantation of agricultural products from the Americas contributed to an increase in the food supply in Europe.

D14916682F824321AA90A8BDA37CC573.description: Overseas products and influences contributed to the development of a consumer culture in Europe.

F4629281EA2B4085B5A2205669C7EB0A.description: The transatlantic slave-labor system expanded in the 17th and 18th centuries as demand for New World products increased

00D6355B6D734CA1B16791ECCF4BDD75.description: European states followed mercantilist policies by exploiting colonies in the New World and elsewhere.

206BBE8CDCBF42928AE2DAF9E344D867.description: The European-dominated worldwide economic network contributed to the agricultural, industrial and consumer revolutions in Europe.

B961667EBD1A47D1BB40927B06142861.description: The development of the market economy led to new financial practices and institutions.

C00A322F343B4150A7D65BBD49C197E2.description: The putting-out system, or cottage industry, expanded as increasing numbers of laborers in homes or workshops produced for markets through merchant intermdiaries or workshop owners.

75A5644443294DFFB896E129F1A2F790.description: The Agricultural Revolution raised productivity and increased the supply of food and other agricultural products.

226168E1A85D497A877D23F250E2FF14.description: Labor and trade in commodities were increasingly freed from traditional restrictions imposed by governments and corporate entities.

200D89826EC1452281EECFF738EDEA5E.description: Early modern Europe developed a market economy that provided the foundation for its global role.

DE2889B999894CAD807C2F786BC222E3.description: The expansion of European commerece accelerated the growth of a worldwide economic network.

070F5F6519664DC3BBE9C04FA6794942.description: Claiming to defend the ideas of the French Revolution, Napoleon Bonaparte, imposed French control over much of the European continent that eventually provoked a nationalistic reaction.

05585BB762B34EBD85446293CFD889C4.description: While many were inspired by the revolution's emphasis on equality and human rights, others condemned its violence and disregard for traditonal authority.

FE41710FCD6F4EC78AD91B0DFCE907F8.description: Revolutionary ideals inspired a slave revolt led by Toussaiant L'Ouverture in the French colony of Saint Domingue, which became the indipendent nation of Haiti in 1804

23CF303066FF42E6B1988786676C250B.description: Women enthusiastically participated in the early phases of the revolution; however, while there were brief improvements in the legal status of women, citizenship in the republic was soon restricted to men.

E9B98FA85A0C4A13B8108777B40B2F0B.description: Revolutionary armies, raised by mass conscription, sought to bring the changes initiated in France to the rest of Europe.

3204DA6C142D4BD3BE00BA41DF27EBB1.description: After the execution of Louis XVI, the radical Jacobin Republic led by Robespierre responded to opposition at home and war abroad by instituting the Reign of Terror, fixing prices and wages, and pursuing a policy of de-Christianization.

D9DDCEC6141645C5AC39145541F29F88.description: The first, or liberal, phase of the French Revolution established a constitutional monarchy, increased popular participation, nationalized the Catholic Church and abolished hereditary privilegegs.

C3F6382B0F5840EF8E9ED084BAECD627.description: The French Revolution resulted from a combination of long-term social and political causes, as well as Enlightenment ideas, exacerbated by short-term fiscal and economic crises.

3604E345F22B47CAA7381A1A5904B680.description: The French Revolution posed a fundamental challenge to Europe's existing political and social order.

3B49DEC779994D06A43E1AAA2FBC4180.description: Rivalry between Britain and France resulted in world wars fought both in Europe and in the colonies, with Britain supplanting France as the greatest European power.

1DCE1759C8704C1FB01D66D834505628.description: Louis XIV's nearly continuous wars, pursuing both dynastic and state interests, provoked a coalition of European powers opposing him.

8A059FDC5C374A2CAC82654E6FD144F0.description: After the Austrian defeat of the Turks in 1683 at the Battle of Vienna, the Ottomans ceased their westward expansion.

14D056AB9E3F4968B71ABD72D2F102D1.description: As a result of the Holy Roman Empire's limitations of sovereignty in the Peace of Westphalia, Prussia rose to power and the Hapsburgs, centered in Austria, shifted their empire eastward.

6431C14BFB4E4B979C47E54E27D72EA9.description: After 1648, dynastic and state interests, along with Europe's expanding colonial empires, influenced the diplomacy of European states and frequently led to war.

0C60C3E5DFCB44D48B98AEC8E4EEDF9C.description: The Dutch Republic developed an oligarchy of urban gentry and rural landholders to promote trade and protect traditional rights.

6A9318638A954C4196922E4DEA7D0E7B.description: The outcome of the English Civil War and the Glorious Revolution protected the rights of gentry and aristocracy from absolutism through assertions of the rights of Parliament.

ADAFE881FAC64F76B31D404531111972.description: Challenges to absolutism resulted in alternative political systems.

DE5863CE10FB458EA5F96591CD1BCA70.description: Peter the Great "westernized" the Russian state and society, transforming political, religious, and cultural institutions; Catherine the Great continued this process.

390D77284F984C17AC0426389BBA64B7.description: The inability of the Polish monarchy to consolidate its authority over the nobility led to Poland's partition by Prussia, Russia, and Austria, and its disappearance from the map of Europe.

2588614F7FF54F67A55E78870B7BA0B3.description: In the 18th century, a number of states in eastern and central Europe experimented with enlightened absolutism

4830868B6C6840BCA6CF21739643831F.description: Louis XIV and his finance minister, Jean-Baptiste Colbert, extended the administrative, financial, military and religious control of the central state over the French population

74F25042ED4344D69E5B79603C6A1CC3.description: Absolute monarchies limited the nobility's participation in goverance but preserved the aristocracy social position and legal privileges.

C8656274F6F94A9B9F5A76C6485237E3.description: In much of Europe, absolute monarchy was established over the course of the 17th and 18th century.

BDC653430268498EBE290E244EC8F11E.description: Different models of political sovereignty affacted the relationship among and between states and idividuals.

68997073D3F849DDBA3225B76CD8D447.description: Reflecting fold ideas and social and economic upheaval, acusations of witchcraft peaked between 1580 and 1650.

7C1AF2B2BC824DF58C3D8D1989F0BBE8.description: Local and church authorities continued to enforce communal norms through rituals of public humiliation

28CCC6FACB78406FBA40D0182BD8D081.description: Leisure activities continued to be organized according to the religious calendar and the agricultural cycle and remained communal in nature.

C5F7E47DDE0B4A7A907489C19E0B29EB.description: Popular culture, leisure activities, and rituals reflecting the persistence of folk ideas reinforced and sometimes challenged communal ties and norms.

AB38E03870CF4FC0B6AD22AC0B0498FB.description: From the late 16th century forward, Europeans responded to economic and environmental challenges, such as the "Little Ice Age," by delaying marriage and childbearing, which restrained population growth and ultimately improved the economic condition of families.

CF0DBB9D24744005B973D0D0B48A3B36.description: The Renaissance and Reformation movements raised debates about female roles in the family, society and the church

686A939FA70C48AA94CB6EFC793FE038.description: Rural and urban households worked as units, with men and women engaged in seperate but complementary tasks.

F88E73B072FF45A4945D2DFB650B1527.description: The family remained the primary social and economic institution of early modern Europe and took several forms, including the nuclear family.

DD5BC1A12C084222AFC67297E631412C.description: Social dislocation, coupled with the weakening of religious institutions during the Reformation, left city governments with the task of regulating public morals.

6C64BB000A4E44D391AC8368459D8A61.description: Migrants to the cities challenged the ability of merchant elites and craft guilds to govern and strained resources.

964283C479864D74981EBEF8B3B91E83.description: Population recovered to pre-Great Plague level in the 16th century, and continuing population pressures contributed to uneven price increase; agricultural commodities increase more sharply than wages, reducing living standars for some.

BEE5B4E70A854E188467CF28F0FB1899.description: Population shifts and growing commerce caused the expansion of cities, which often found their traditional political and social structures tressed by the growth.

B70EB84599974FE1A63662DE42390140.description: The attempts of landlords to increase their revenues by restricting or abolishing the traditional rights of peasants led to revolt.

EADC2B00714F4BBEB608CFC386B1A9E8.description: As western Europe moved toward a free peasantry and commercial agricuture, serfdom was codified in the east, where nobles continued to dominate economic life on large esates.

1FBD3D854B8F470F9C26B9DCE7D208DB.description: The price revolution contributed to the accumulatikon of capital and the expansion of the market economu through the commercialization of agriculture, which benefited large landowners in western Europe.

509B2FB991ED40F78D44DED3A7312ED1.description: Subsistence agriculture was the rule in most areas, with three-crop field rotation in the north and two-crop rotation in the Medierranean; in many cases, farmers paid rent and labor servies for their land.

83A96EC092AE4A799131302A0189FDB8.description: Most Europeans derived their lievelidhood from agriculture and oriented their lives around the seasons, the village, or the manor, although economic changes began to alter rural production and power.

7E7DE2AC179A4770AA88AB2A98EE7FD9.description: Hierarchy and status continued to define social power and perceptions in rural and urban settings.

EA962CDDCE1F4965AC7C8DCCD572A63F.description: The growth of commerce produced a new economic elite, which related to traditonal elities in different ways in Europe's various geographic regions.

31A02646318A46D4A0EBB63F8768B475.description: Innovations in banking and finance promoted the growth of urban financial centers and a money economy.

D2BA3AC2FA3E4178AD1C76A586B18042.description: Economic change produced new social pattersn, while traditions of hierarcy and status persisted.

34BA432835D34FFD8C93C4135C758C77.description: European society and the  experiences of everyday life were increasingly shaped by commercial and agricultural capitalism, notwithstanding the persistence of medieval social and economic structures.

2BA3D9BE1BE240A4AB54CFD08F5008C9.description: Europeans expanded the African slave  trade in response to the establishment of a plantation economy in the Americas and demographic catastrophes among indigenous peoples.

852B428BFD3C47CAB018712DAA8090F8.description: The exchange of new plants, animals, and disease - the Columbian Exchange - creased economic opportunities for Europeans and faciliated European subjugation and estruction of indigenous peoples, particualry in the Americas.

16C33A365F3A4DBD8FA0D02D9521FCDA.description: The exchange of goods shifted the center of economic power in Europe from the Mediterranean to the Atlantic states and brough the latter into an expanding world economy.

8E09358AFCE34DE5A6E9D3AAD7CD6561.description: Europe's colonial expansion led to a global exchange of goods, flora, fauna, cultural practices, and diseases, resulting in the destriction of some indigenous civilizations, a shift toward European dominance, and the expansion of the slave trade.

C73006984FC14C5BAA8F58034B825AF2.description: The competition for trade led to conflicts and rivalries among European powers

D654F3F5CA9345A7999A1DD4BCAEA3A8.description: The Atlantic nations of France, England, and the Netherlands followed by establishing their own colonies and trading networks to complete with Portuguese and Spanish dominance.

8879BAEA7DFA4F688451BFC39590971E.description: The Spanish established colonies across the Americas, the Caribbean, and the Pacific, which made Spain a dominant state in Europe.

365E6BA8C15D489DBA95E3CFD636754C.description: The Portuguese established a commercial network along the African coast, in South and East Asia and in South America

2724E57087054F968DFCC9EB6AC8D918.description: Europeans established overseas empires and trade networks through coercion and negotiation.

DAB9733BAB3E40F39B7EE9991BFF7D61.description: Advances in navigation, cartography and military technology allowed Europeans to establish overseas colonies and empires

B45E53062747412BB1B5C69D93911E34.description: Christianity served as a stimulus for exploration as governments and religious authorities sough to spread the faith and counter Islam, and as a justification for the physical and cultural subjugation of indigenous civilizations.

D393AB19B8D645F195D6118FBFCC8333.description: The rise of mercantilism gave the state a new role in promoting commercial development and the acquisition of colonies overseas.

674A07AD79CD4E5E96A7FC89DEAF0E3A.description: European states sought direct access to gold and spices and luxury goods as a means to enhance personal wealth and state power.

A92BDA4CBBE94BEFB3586D5F52BED2A3.description: European nations were driven by commercial and relilgious motives to explore overseas territories and establish colonies.

EE34BEDCD50B487984E24542A8F8EF2B.description: Europeans explored and settled overseas territories,  encountering and interacting with indigenous populations.

1AB80487011743CD95A1311C974D8767.description: A few states, such as France with the Edict of Nantes, allowed religious pluralism in order to maintain domestic peace.

FAEB9B4281284A19B3920F024F930DE1.description: States exploited religious conflicts to promot political and economic interests.

1B2A830B46DB42C9BAD17E14A94D43DD.description: The efforts of the Habsburg rulers failed to restore Cathollic unity accros Europe

2C0D42C2834B430B88A288ECC797DBF6.description: Issues of religious reform exacerbated conflicts between the monarchy and the nobility, as in the French wars of religion

62FFD1341EC048818CC5D2372EBA436B.description: Conflicts among religious groups overlapped with political and economic competition within and among states

D216C8E7FCC9456BAE6F3A407EBB9026.description: Religious conflicts became the basis of challenging the monarchs' control of religious institutions.

8E2959D28F0C4123AF5A3D9150764C83.description: Some protestants, including Calvin and the Anabaptist, refused to recognize the subordination of the church to the state.

2BA8A2005A6D4B5E9754722F2FDF4991.description: Monarchs and prices, such as the English rulers Henry VIII and Elizabeth I, initiated religious reform from the top down (magisterial) in an effort to excercise greater control over religious life and morality

133FC7E4CF18472F8BBE1A4C7897AC09.description: Religious reform both increased state control of religious institutions and provided justifications for challenging state authority

A9F15F60733645169B54A7BF4C942479.description: The Catholic Reformation, exemplified by the Jesuit Order and the Council of Trent, revived the church but cemented the division within Christianity.

69E96F5838CE4BCDBE312FD75ED74798.description: Reformers Martin Luther and John Calvin, as well as religious radicals such as Anabaptists, criticized Catholic abuses and established new interpretations of Christian doctrine and practice

DA3EA52072274699BBB19C3A554BF31A.description: Christian humanism embodied in the writings of Erasmus, employed Renaissance learning in the service of religious reform.

Advances in military technology (i.e. the military revolution) led to new forms of warfare including greater reliance on infantry, firearms, mobile cannon, and more elaborate fortifications, all financed by heavier taxation and requiring a larger beureaucracy. Technology, tactics, and strtegies tipped the balance of power toward states able to marshal sufficient resources for the new military environment.

In the oral culture of pesants, a belief that the cosmos was governed by devine and demonic forces persisted.
